The paper deals with low-rank factorization of matrices, which is a problem in linear algebra and optimization. The use of differential privacy techniques makes it relevant to the sub-categories of data structures (cs.DS), information theory (cs.IT), and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the privacy implications of the algorithms, which makes it relevant to the sub-categories of cryptography (cs.CR) and data mining (cs.DM).
